##Under the double shadow of epidemic situation and disaster, Chinese and American Science and technology companies have no choice but to resist

Weixin caijingEleven

The function introduction by "CAIJING" Magazine Company Industry Report team to create, discuss the success or failure of the enterprise, explore the rise and fall of the industry, promote sunshine business

No one can predict exactly when the crisis will come, especially for technology companies. It is important to maintain the ability to withstand risks and explore new markets. When the stock market falls, only abundant cash flow can help the enterprise to resist the risk

Liu Yiqin, Chen Xiaoxiao | Wen

By Cheryl Yung | editor

The Gist:

1. Technological innovation is the current economic development of the main track, but also in the past few years the US stock market rose the main gainer, US stocks rose for 11 years, the Chinese stock market, technology stocks rose for two years in a row. U. S. stocks fell sharply, the development of the technology industry inevitably affected.

2. Apple was the biggest faller among the top five U.S. tech companies, shedding $99.6 billion in market value after the stock market meltdown.

3. There are also a number of Chinese technology companies listed in the US, and China will outperform US technology companies slightly because they are revenue-protected and dependent on the Chinese market.

4. The short-term impact of the decline in US stocks on a-shares was limited. A shares do not follow the outside market, the United States stocks rose during the 11-year period a shares volatility is not obvious.

5. The reason why the current trend of a-shares is relatively independent, because of the recent transfer of household savings, new and old infrastructure development and other policies have been rolled out one after another. This is particularly good for Chinese technology companies.

6. Buying back shares and stabilising share prices can support companies through tough market cycles. But no one can predict exactly when the crisis will come, especially technology companies, to maintain the ability to resist risk and open up new markets are very important.

Affected by the spread of the new coronavirus and the oil price war, at 9:34 a.m. Eastern time on March 9, the three major U.S. stock indexes all dropped more than 7% , triggering the fuse. The so-called circuit breaker mechanism, colloquially, is that when the stock market falls to a certain extent, the market automatically stops trading for a period of time, may be a few minutes, may also be the end of the whole day trading. The main aim is to prevent further panic spreading to the market to bring more impact.

Three months after the "black Monday" of 1987, the US introduced a three-way index circuit breaker, with 7 per cent, 13 per cent and 20 per cent losses. After more than three decades in the U.S. stock market, it was only once before that that U.S. stocks actually triggered a circuit breaker: On Oct. 27,1997, Dow Jones Industrial Average plunged 7.18 percent to close at 7,161.15, the biggest drop since 1915. On March 9th investors saw history once again.

Leading U.S. tech stocks continued to fall, with Facebook down 6.4% , Amazon down 5.29% , apple down 7.91% , google down 6.17% and netflix down 6.09% by the end of March 10. The five most valuable tech giants lost $321.6 billion overnight.

US listed Chinese technology companies were also affected, with Alibaba down 3.45 per cent, Baidu down 6.23 per cent, jd.com down 5.34 per cent and Weilai down 7.04 per cent.

In the past year, China and the United States have competed in technology, including 5G, chips and artificial intelligence. Technology stocks have also been the main gainers in the past few years, rising for 11 years in the U.S. and for two years in China. U. S. stocks fell sharply, the development of the technology industry inevitably affected.

Hou Xiaotian, founder of T.H. Capital, told Caijing that when the stock market is down, only abundant cash flow can help companies fend off risks.

11-year bull market in U.S. TECH STOCKS TO END?

Yang Delong, chief strategist at Southern Fund, told the Financial Times that the circuit breaker had a huge impact on most U.S. stocks, and particularly on technology stocks, which have risen so much in the past decade, most profitable.

U.S. stocks have risen for 11 years in a row, and several capital market analysts told Caijing that it was time for a correction. This is a reasonable adjustment stage, but at the same time the global spread of the new crown epidemic, may let the market into panic.

Apple was the biggest faller among the top five U.S. tech companies, shedding $99.6 billion in market value. Apple is the only consumer hardware company among the top five U.S. tech companies. Of course, it would not be fair to put the blame for Apple's stock market decline squarely on the American market. On February 18, apple announced that the global iPhone supply was strained by the outbreak and that it would miss its revenue target of $63 billion to $67 billion for the second quarter.

From Feb. 1 to Feb. 9, Apple closed all retail stores in mainland China for a full nine days. As of March 10,38 mainland Apple Store were open for business from 11 to 18(normal business hours are 10 to 22) , four other stores remained closed, including in Tianjin and Suzhou, for reasons apple did not disclose.

The outbreak has made it difficult for apple not only to sell, but also to produce, and several apple supply chain companies, including Foxconn, have yet to fully resume operations.

As the China epidemic draws to a close, the meltdowns have dealt apple another blow. Hou Xiaotian's view is that a fall in capital markets and a slowdown in economic activity will affect personal consumption, "just-needed personal consumption will not be affected too much, and spending on high-priced electronics will be hit, " a CICC analyst told Caijing. Technology companies have different business models, "If it's purely online and the unit price is not high, the impact will be small, and apple will be affected a lot. "

In addition to consumer electronics, U.S. tech companies, such as Google and Facebook, make most of their revenue from advertising, and Hou believes advertisers will be hurt by a downturn in the stock market and a contraction in economic activity.

In recent years, technology companies have begun to shift their focus from technology empowerment to new technologies, including artificial intelligence, big data, and cloud computing. The new business will also be affected by client retrenchment.

In addition to US technology companies, there are many Chinese technology companies listed in the US, including Alibaba, Baidu, JD.com, CTRIP and so on. Yang thinks chinext will outperform US technology companies slightly because they are revenue-protected and dependent on the Chinese market.

One potential risk for Chinese companies is that US capital markets will reduce investment in Chinese companies. Chen Kaifeng, chief strategy officer of Haiyin capital of the United States, recently participated in a number of activities in the United States financial industry. He found that many senior figures of American investment institutions all had negative comments about China. He judged that, "Contagion, not just in the US but around the world, is likely to reduce investment in China, with ordinary investors buying less shares in Chinese companies.

A shares have little short-term impact

Compared with the almost all-green U. S. stocks and stocks in China, a share performance is much more stable. The Shanghai Composite Index was up about 0.5 per cent at the start of trading on March 10, with the other two gaining slightly more than the Shanghai composite.

Combined with the views of many investors, the short-term impact of the decline in U. S. stocks on a-shares is limited. A broker told CAIJING that although the outbreak triggered a global liquidity crisis, but a shares do not follow the outside market, the United States stocks rose during the 11-year fluctuations in a shares were not obvious. In addition, the current low oil price is conducive to economic recovery and monetary policy flexibility, increased interest rate cut space, on the a shares are more favorable.

A secondary market investor told CAIJING that the reason why a-shares are relatively independent is because of the recent transfer of household savings, new and old infrastructure and other policies are being rolled out one after another. This is particularly good for Chinese technology companies. The government is continuing to provide favorable policies to the technology industry and has launched more than $25 trillion in infrastructure projects.

Compared to the U. S. stocks and stocks in China, a shares of the current stability is good, especially technology stocks. A-SHARE technology shares have surged since trading resumed after the Lunar New Year holiday this year. In particular, 5G, semiconductors, new energy vehicles and other fields.

At the end of February this year, the Ministry of Industry and Information Technology held a teleconference. One of the important issues was to speed up the development of 5G and do a good job in resuming production in the information and communications industry. Since then, the 5g concept across the board. ZTE's share price reached a record high of 50.11 yuan, up 41% this year. Other trading caps included yitong century, lutong video, Guanghetong, Wuhan Fangu, Aowei Communications, fiberhome communications and Tongyu Communications.

Most investors told the CAIJING reporter that in the past two years a-share technology stocks have been in a bull market, with a large cumulative increase and generally high valuations. If we combine this factor, in the long run, a sharp fall in global stock markets would still trigger a correction in these stocks. "The logic that a shares are a safe haven because of the fall in the external market is weak, " one investor told CAIJING.

These investors believe that affected by the epidemic, investors risk appetite reduced, will be more cautious. This means that taking a longer-term perspective accelerates the divergence of these tech stocks, "which is good up and bad down, depending on performance. "

The CICC analyst mentioned that China's import and export technology companies will also be affected if global demand falls short, and, "sooner or later, China will face problems like the US, such as insufficient demand, a widening gap between rich and poor, and excessive debt levels. "

Yang Delong believes that for technology stocks, the main focus is on future performance growth, and this depends on technology, management, R & D and other advantages can help companies in the future release performance. If you just fry the concept or technology can not break through, can not open the market, the stock price will fall back.

Ample cash flow is the antidote to short-term risk

For the enterprise, the capital market fluctuation biggest influence is the fund-raising channel contraction. In addition, the spread of the epidemic will hit some industries'revenue, at this time, corporate cash flow capacity is crucial.

Yang believes that U.S. tech giants, including Apple, have a lot of cash on their books and may increase their buybacks to keep their share prices stable in the short term. What's more, these tech powerhouses have risen sharply over the past decade and are sitting on a lot of liquidity.

It is a routine operation for companies to buy back shares. Typically, companies buy back shares when they are undervalued, which is an effective means of shareholder return for big companies. "Now the price is low, buy back cheap, more cost-effective, " Yang said.

Companies'accelerated share buybacks have also helped offset concerns about slowing growth. Throughout 2019, apple spent more than $66 billion on share buybacks, three times as much as Microsoft, Google, Amazon and facebook combined.

Analysts generally believe that apple's share buyback is intended to offset weak growth. The IPHONE, apple's mainstay business, continued to slow during this period.

Apple's net income for the third quarter of 2019 was $10.044 BN, down 13 per cent from $11.519 BN A year earlier. The IPHONE, which accounted for the largest share of revenue, was $25.99 BN, down 12 per cent from $29.47 BN A year earlier, and 48.3 per cent, below 50 per cent for the first time.

Not just apple, but tech giants have been on a buying spree since the third quarter of 2018. Twenty technology companies spent more than $261 billion on share buybacks between the third quarter of 2018 and the third quarter of 2019, according to data released by S & P Capital Iq, a third party financial information firm, is the most active area for share buybacks in the United States.

Buying back shares and stabilising share prices can also support companies through tough market cycles.

Alibaba and Baidu have good cash flow. As of December 31,2019, Baidu had 135.9 billion yuan in cash, cash equivalents, restricted funds and short-term investments, and 10.1 billion yuan in free cash flow, according to the financial report. Over the same period, Alibaba's cash, cash equivalents and short-term investments amounted to 351.9 billion yuan, up about 120 billion yuan from the previous quarter, mainly due to its listing in Hong Kong at the end of November, which raised more than 90 billion yuan.

Jd.com's cash flow is relatively weak, with revenue of 576.9 billion yuan for Jd.com in 2019, up 24.9 percent from a year earlier, and free cash flow rising to 19.5 billion yuan, the company reported.

JD.com is a heavy asset company and relies on cash flow, so it does not set aside much cash. But the outbreak has had a positive impact on e-commerce platforms such as JD.com. "The self-employed model in JD.com has performed relatively well in this epidemic, " Xu Lei, a CEO  of JD.com retail group, said at an earnings call on March 3,2020, predicting that net revenue in the first quarter of this year would grow by more than 10 per cent from a year earlier. On March 6, Tiger Securities released a report saying that JD.com has become one of the few e-commerce platforms under the epidemic that can guarantee customers'normal order and distribution, relying on a self-built logistics and distribution system.

Other tech companies are looking for ways to ease their cash flow. Travel Industry companies such as CTRIP have been hit hard by the outbreak. On March 9, Sun Jie, CEO of CTRIP group, issued an internal letter to employees saying that starting this month, she and Chairman of the Board, Co founder of ctrip group, will start earning zero salaries, at the same time, the company's top management also offered a voluntary pay cut, a minimum of half until the industry recovers; other employees suspended pay increases.

At the beginning of the outbreak, Sun Jie said, ctrip into the phone twenty times, hundreds of millions of people unsubscribe, the company refund advance capital more than 1 billion orders of magnitude. CTRIP is hoping to help its partners in the industry return cash ahead of time by pre-selling their products for future trips, CTRIP CMO SUMPA said at a press conference on March 5, through the worst of the outbreak.

On March 9th CTRIP's shares fell 9.18% to $15.8 billion. As of September 30,2019, CTRIP had a balance of 61 billion yuan ($8.5 billion) in cash, cash equivalents, restricted cash and short-term investments, with no fourth-quarter results yet.

New Technology requires continued investment, and in order to grow rapidly and capture the market, many technology companies have in the past few years chosen to increase their investment or to use subsidies to attract new customers. This can increase first-mover advantage when capital markets are flush with funds or when cash-flow operations are stable. But no one can predict exactly when the crisis will come, and maintaining risk tolerance is just as important as opening new markets.

(also contributed by our correspondent Zhou Yuan)
